B.a2N=new A.lO("QuantumLab provides two simulation modes:\n\n\u2022 Educational Mode (default): Standard |0\u27e9 initialization with standard measurement. This is clearer for learning.\n\n\u2022 PFQVS Mode (advanced): Perlin initialization + decoherence + importance sampling. Shows how real-world noise affects quantum algorithms.\n\nBoth modes use the O(N) pair-iteration gate execution from Layer 2.\n\nThe Grover's search and Deutsch-Jozsa implementations use the PFQVS measurement system for more physically-motivated results.",null)
B.a2O=new A.lO('In standard quantum simulators, qubits start in the |0\u27e9 state \u2014 a mathematically perfect, noise-free initialization. Real quantum hardware, however, has initialization errors.\n\nPFQVS initializes quantum states using 3D Perlin noise, a technique borrowed from computer graphics (invented by Ken Perlin in 1983 for the movie Tron). Each amplitude in the state vector is computed as:\n\n  \u03c8[i] = perlin(i/N, 0.1, seed\xb70.001) + i\xb7perlin((i/N+0.5)%1, 0.2, seed\xb70.001)\n\nwhere perlin(x, y, z) is 3D gradient noise. This produces smooth, deterministic, reproducible initial states that approximate the "noisy" initialization of real quantum hardware.\n\nThe state is then normalized: \u03c8 \u2192 \u03c8/||\u03c8||.\n\nBenefit: PFQVS states are seeded (deterministic for a given seed) but non-trivial, making them useful for studying how algorithms perform under initialization noise.',null)
B.a2P=new A.lO("Standard measurement samples from Born-rule probabilities P(i) = |\u03c8[i]|\xb2. PFQVS uses FFT-based importance sampling to reduce measurement variance:\n\n1. Compute Born-rule probabilities: P[i] = |\u03c8[i]|\xb2\n2. Compute the DFT of the probability distribution\n3. Keep only the top k spectral components (k = N \xd7 spectralFraction)\n4. Inverse DFT to get a spectral mask M[i]\n5. Blend: Q[i] = P[i] + \u03b1 \xd7 M[i]\n6. Sample from Q instead of P\n\nThis biases sampling toward the dominant modes of the probability distribution, reducing the number of shots needed for accurate estimates of high-probability states.\n\nParameter \u03b1 controls the blend strength (default 0.5). When \u03b1 = 0, this reduces to standard Born-rule sampling.",null)
B.a2Q=new A.lO("Real qubits lose coherence over time \u2014 a process called decoherence. PFQVS models this using octave-weighted Perlin noise that evolves with circuit depth.\n\nFor each amplitude \u03c8[i], a damping factor is computed:\n\n  damping[i] = exp(-|E(i, t)| \xd7 dt)\n\nwhere E(i, t) is multi-octave Perlin noise:\n  E(i, t) = \u03a3_{o=1}^{octaves} (1/2^o) \xd7 perlin(i/N \xd7 2^o, 0.1\xd7o, seed + t\xd70.01)\n\nKey properties:\n  \u2022 Time-dependent: decoherence pattern changes with circuit depth t\n  \u2022 Spatially correlated: nearby basis states experience similar decoherence\n  \u2022 Multi-scale: octave weighting captures both local and global noise\n  \u2022 Controllable: dt parameter controls decoherence strength",null)
B.a2R=new A.lO("PFQVS (Perlin-Fourier Quantum Virtual Simulation) is a novel quantum circuit simulation approach developed for the novum-qvm library, published on PyPI. It combines three mathematical techniques to create a more physically-motivated quantum simulator:\n\n1. Perlin noise for state initialization\n2. Fourier-domain (FFT) gate execution\n3. Spectral decoherence modeling\n\nQuantumLab uses PFQVS as its core simulation engine, ported from Python/NumPy to Dart.",null)
B.a2S=new A.lO("Standard simulators build full 2^n \xd7 2^n matrices via Kronecker products (O(4^n) space!). PFQVS uses an efficient O(N) pair-iteration algorithm:\n\nFor a single-qubit gate U on qubit q:\n  1. Identify pairs of basis states that differ only in qubit q\n  2. For each pair (i, j) where i has qubit q = 0 and j has qubit q = 1:\n     [\u03c8'[i]]   [U\u2080\u2080  U\u2080\u2081] [\u03c8[i]]\n     [\u03c8'[j]] = [U\u2081\u2080  U\u2081\u2081] [\u03c8[j]]\n  3. No Kronecker product needed!\n\nTime complexity: O(2^n) instead of O(4^n)\nSpace complexity: O(1) extra (in-place update)\n\nFor CNOT gates, PFQVS uses computational-basis permutation: if the control qubit is |1\u27e9, flip the target bit in the basis state index. This is also O(N).\n\nThe \"FFT\" in the name refers to the gate cache system, which precomputes Fourier-domain representations of gates for potential future optimizations with circulant gate decompositions.",null)
B.a2T=new A.lO("Library: novum-qvm v1.2.0 (PyPI)\nAuthor: Amin Alogaili\nLicense: MIT\nRepository: github.com/iriszimmerfrau-collab/novum-qvm\n\nThe Dart implementation in QuantumLab is a faithful port of the Python original, optimized for mobile performance with List<Complex> instead of NumPy arrays.\n\nMax qubits: 8 (256 amplitudes = ~4 KB memory)\nGate execution: < 1ms for all supported gates\nMeasurement: < 10ms for 1024 shots",null)
